There are two problems in your code that I can see: 

 1. There is no transaction around your controller call, and so, you are trying to persist an `Flashcard` entity that is referencing a detached `User`
 2. Neither side of the association is marked as `@JsonIgnore`, so JSON serialization fails either with a `StackOverflowError`, if `spring.jpa.open-in-view` is `true`, or with a `LazyInitializationException` otherwise (this is likely the core issue, but I cannot be sure, since the root cause is not included in the stack trace you provided)


A simpler way to do what you want would be: 

```
@Transactional
@ResponseStatus(CREATED)
@PostMapping(&quot;/users/{id}/flashcards&quot;)
public Flashcard createFlashcard(@PathVariable(&quot;id&quot;) int userId, @RequestBody Flashcard flashcard) {
    flashcard.setUser(userRepository.getReferenceById(userId));
    return flashcardRepository.save(flashcard);
}
```

coupled with 

```
@Data
@Entity
public class User {
    
    @JsonIgnore
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY, mappedBy = &quot;user&quot;)
    private List&lt;Flashcard&gt; flashcards;
}
```

Since you marked both sides to be lazy, you might need `@JsonIgnore` on both sides. 

BTW `@OnDelete(action = OnDeleteAction.CASCADE)` on `Flashcard.user` doesn&#39;t really make sense (what it is saying is &#39;when one of the user&#39;s flashcard is deleted, please delete the entire user as well&#39;, which I&#39;m pretty sure is NOT what you intended)

